.

``
Whether
it
's
$
0
billion
or
$
0.0
billion
,
it
does
n't
matter
.

It
's
huge
.
''

Consider
the
growth
of
portables
,
which
now
comprise
00
%
of
all
personal
computer
sales
.

Laptops
--
generally
anything
under
00
pounds
--
have
become
the
fastest-growing
personal
computer
segment
,
with
sales
doubling
this
year
.

Responding
to
that
demand
,
however
,
has
led
to
a
variety
of
compromises
.

Making
computers
smaller
often
means
sacrificing
memory
.

It
also
has
precluded
use
of
the
faster
,
more
powerful
microprocessors
found
in
increasing
numbers
of
desktop
machines
.

Size
and
weight
considerations
also
have
limited
screen
displays
.

The
competitive
sniping
can
get
pretty
petty
at
times
.

A
<_UNK>
spokesman
,
for
example
,
criticizes
the
Atari
Portfolio
because
it
requires
three
batteries
while
the
<_UNK>
needs
only
two
.

Both
<_UNK>
are
dismissed
by
notebook
makers
,
who
argue
that
they
're
too
small
--
a
problem
<_UNK>
also
encountered
in
focus
groups
,
admits
Gerry
Purdy
,
director
of
marketing
.

<_UNK>
,
trying
to
avoid
the
``
gadget
''
label
,
responded
with
the
tag
line
,
``
The
<_UNK>
PC
--
a
Very
Big
Computer
.
''

Despite
the
sniping
,
few
question
the
inevitability
of
the
move
to
small
machines
that
do
n't
make
compromises
.

Toward
that
end
,
experts
say
the
real
battle
will
take
place
between
center-stage
players
like
Toshiba
,
Zenith
and
now
